---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { TAX_YEAR, SITE_NAME } from '../../lib/constants';

const title = 'State Income Tax Comparison: All 50 US States Ranked';
const description = `Compare income tax rates across all 50 US states for ${TAX_YEAR}. See no-tax states, flat-tax states, progressive brackets, and highest marginal rates at a glance.`;

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: title,
  description,
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: SITE_NAME },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: SITE_NAME },
  datePublished: '2026-01-01',
  dateModified: '2026-01-15',
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} schema={schema}>
  <article class="px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="prose prose-slate dark:prose-invert mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h1>State Income Tax Comparison: All 50 States</h1>

      <p>
        Where you live has a massive impact on your take-home pay. State income tax rates range from 0% to
        over 13%, and the differences add up to thousands of dollars each year. This guide compares income
        tax structures across all 50 states and the District of Columbia, organized by tax type, so you can
        see exactly how your state stacks up.
      </p>

      <p>
        Use our state-specific calculators to see your exact take-home pay. Try the
        <a href="/take-home-pay-calculator/">take-home pay calculator</a> and select your state for a
        personalized breakdown.
      </p>

      <h2 id="no-income-tax-states">The 9 States with No Income Tax</h2>

      <p>
        These states do not levy any tax on wage or salary income, making them popular destinations for
        high earners and retirees:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>Alaska</strong> - No income tax; also distributes an annual Permanent Fund Dividend to residents</li>
        <li><strong>Florida</strong> - No income tax; constitutionally prohibited from enacting one</li>
        <li><strong>Nevada</strong> - No income tax; revenue comes from gaming and sales taxes</li>
        <li><strong>New Hampshire</strong> - No tax on wages (previously taxed interest and dividends, but that tax was fully phased out)</li>
        <li><strong>South Dakota</strong> - No income tax; also no corporate income tax</li>
        <li><strong>Tennessee</strong> - No tax on wages (the Hall Tax on investment income was fully repealed in 2021)</li>
        <li><strong>Texas</strong> - No income tax; constitutionally prohibited; relies heavily on property and sales tax</li>
        <li><strong>Washington</strong> - No income tax on wages; has a capital gains tax on high earners enacted in 2022</li>
        <li><strong>Wyoming</strong> - No income tax; also no corporate income tax</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        Living in a no-tax state does not automatically mean a lower total tax burden. These states often
        compensate with higher property taxes, sales taxes, or other fees. For a deeper analysis, see our
        guide on <a href="/guides/moving-to-a-no-income-tax-state/">moving to a no-income-tax state</a>.
      </p>

      <h2 id="flat-tax-states">Flat-Tax States (Single Rate)</h2>

      <p>
        These states apply a single tax rate to all taxable income regardless of how much you earn. Flat
        taxes are simpler to calculate and have become increasingly popular, with several states recently
        converting from progressive systems:
      </p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>State</th>
            <th>Flat Rate</th>
            <th>Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Arizona</td><td>2.5%</td><td>Reduced from graduated rates in 2023</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Colorado</td><td>4.4%</td><td>Reduced from 4.55% in 2024</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Georgia</td><td>5.39%</td><td>Transitioning to 4.99% flat rate by 2029</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Idaho</td><td>5.695%</td><td>Converted from graduated in 2023</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Illinois</td><td>4.95%</td><td>Flat rate mandated by state constitution</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Indiana</td><td>3.05%</td><td>Gradually reducing; was 3.23% in 2023</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Iowa</td><td>3.8%</td><td>Transitioning to flat rate; was graduated</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Kentucky</td><td>4.0%</td><td>Reduced from 5% in 2023</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Michigan</td><td>4.25%</td><td>Long-standing flat rate</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Mississippi</td><td>4.7%</td><td>Transitioning to lower flat rate</td></tr>
          <tr><td>North Carolina</td><td>4.5%</td><td>Gradually reducing; was 5.25% in 2022</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Pennsylvania</td><td>3.07%</td><td>One of the lowest flat rates</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Utah</td><td>4.65%</td><td>Reduced from 4.85% in 2023</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Massachusetts</td><td>5.0%</td><td>Plus 4% surtax on income over $1M</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="progressive-tax-states">Progressive-Tax States (Graduated Brackets)</h2>

      <p>
        The remaining states use graduated bracket systems similar to the federal tax code, where higher
        income is taxed at progressively higher rates. Here are the states with the highest top marginal
        rates:
      </p>

      <h3 id="highest-marginal-rates">States with Highest Top Marginal Rates</h3>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>State</th>
            <th>Top Rate</th>
            <th>Top Bracket Starts At</th>
            <th>Number of Brackets</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>California</td><td>13.3%</td><td>$1,000,000</td><td>10</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hawaii</td><td>11.0%</td><td>$200,000</td><td>12</td></tr>
          <tr><td>New Jersey</td><td>10.75%</td><td>$1,000,000</td><td>7</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Oregon</td><td>9.9%</td><td>$125,000</td><td>4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Minnesota</td><td>9.85%</td><td>$193,240</td><td>4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>New York</td><td>10.9%</td><td>$25,000,000</td><td>9</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Vermont</td><td>8.75%</td><td>$229,500</td><td>4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>District of Columbia</td><td>10.75%</td><td>$1,000,000</td><td>7</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Wisconsin</td><td>7.65%</td><td>$405,550</td><td>4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Maine</td><td>7.15%</td><td>$58,050</td><td>3</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3 id="lowest-marginal-rates">States with Lowest Top Marginal Rates (Progressive)</h3>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>State</th>
            <th>Top Rate</th>
            <th>Brackets</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>North Dakota</td><td>2.5%</td><td>4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Arkansas</td><td>3.9%</td><td>3</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Alabama</td><td>5.0%</td><td>3</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Louisiana</td><td>4.25%</td><td>3</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Oklahoma</td><td>4.75%</td><td>6</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="tax-comparison-75k">How $75,000 Is Taxed Across States</h2>

      <p>
        To put these rates in perspective, here is what a single filer earning $75,000 would pay in state
        income tax across a selection of states:
      </p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>State</th>
            <th>Approx. State Tax</th>
            <th>Effective Rate</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Texas</td><td>$0</td><td>0.0%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Florida</td><td>$0</td><td>0.0%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Pennsylvania</td><td>$2,303</td><td>3.07%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Arizona</td><td>$1,875</td><td>2.5%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Illinois</td><td>$3,713</td><td>4.95%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Colorado</td><td>$3,300</td><td>4.4%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>New York</td><td>$3,534</td><td>4.7%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>California</td><td>$3,131</td><td>4.2%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Oregon</td><td>$6,178</td><td>8.2%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hawaii</td><td>$4,784</td><td>6.4%</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>
        Notice that Oregon and Hawaii impose significantly higher effective rates even at moderate incomes
        because their top brackets kick in at relatively low thresholds. California's effective rate at
        $75,000 is moderate because its highest brackets only apply to very high earners.
      </p>

      <h2 id="total-tax-burden">Beyond Income Tax: Total State Tax Burden</h2>

      <p>
        Comparing states solely by income tax is misleading. States without income tax often have higher
        taxes elsewhere:
      </p>

      <h3 id="property-tax">Property Tax</h3>
      <p>
        Texas, which has no income tax, has one of the highest average property tax rates at 1.60% of
        assessed home value. On a $400,000 home, that is $6,400 per year. New Hampshire's effective
        property tax rate is even higher at around 1.86%. Compare this to Hawaii's rate of just 0.29%.
        Learn more in our <a href="/guides/understanding-property-tax/">property tax guide</a>.
      </p>

      <h3 id="sales-tax">Sales Tax</h3>
      <p>
        Combined state and local sales tax rates vary from 0% (Delaware, Montana, Oregon, New Hampshire)
        to over 9% (Tennessee, Louisiana, Arkansas, Washington, Alabama when including local rates). A high
        sales tax disproportionately affects lower-income residents. See our
        <a href="/guides/sales-tax-explained/">sales tax guide</a> for details.
      </p>

      <h3 id="other-taxes-fees">Other Taxes and Fees</h3>
      <p>
        States also vary on vehicle registration fees, gas taxes, estate taxes, excise taxes, and various
        fees. Washington state has one of the highest gas taxes in the nation. Florida charges a document
        stamp tax on real estate transactions.
      </p>

      <h2 id="state-tax-trends">State Tax Trends</h2>

      <p>
        Several significant trends are shaping state tax policy:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Flat tax conversions:</strong> Multiple states have switched from graduated to flat income
          tax systems, including Arizona, Iowa, and Mississippi, often with plans to further reduce rates.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Rate reductions:</strong> States like North Carolina, Indiana, and Kentucky are on
          multi-year schedules to lower their rates, sometimes contingent on revenue targets being met.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Millionaire surtaxes:</strong> Massachusetts added a 4% surtax on income over $1 million
          in 2023. Similar proposals have been considered in other states.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Remote work complications:</strong> With more workers living in one state and working for
          employers in another, state tax rules for remote workers remain complex and evolving.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="remote-workers">State Tax for Remote Workers</h2>

      <p>
        If you work remotely, you generally owe income tax to the state where you physically perform the
        work (your residence state). However, some states have "convenience of the employer" rules that
        tax you in the employer's state even if you never set foot there. New York is the most notable
        example. If you split time between states, you may need to file returns in multiple states and claim
        credits to avoid double taxation.
      </p>

      <h2 id="choosing-right-state">Choosing the Right State for You</h2>

      <p>
        When comparing states, consider these factors:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Your income level (high earners benefit most from no-tax states)</li>
        <li>Whether you own or rent (property tax matters more for homeowners)</li>
        <li>Your spending habits (sales tax matters more for high spenders)</li>
        <li>Cost of living differences (a lower tax state may have higher housing costs)</li>
        <li>Quality of public services (education, infrastructure, healthcare access)</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Use our <a href="/take-home-pay-calculator/">take-home pay calculator</a> to compare your net pay
        across states, or explore <a href="/income-tax-calculator/">income tax calculations</a> for any
        state and filing status.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
